<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Lacking Natural Simplicity (Posts about horror)</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/</link><description></description><atom:link href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/categories/horror.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><copyright>Contents © 2020 &lt;a href="mailto:tkurtbond@gmail.com"&gt;T. Kurt Bond&lt;/a&gt; </copyright><lastBuildDate>Sat, 14 Mar 2020 05:45:30 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>Karl Edward Wagner's Horror Stories</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;I primarily know &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Edward_Wagner"&gt;Karl Edward Wagner&lt;/a&gt;'s work from his “heroic
fantasy” &lt;a class="footnote-reference brackets" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/#hf" id="id1"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt; novels and stories of &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Edward_Wagner#Kane,_the_Mystic_Swordsman"&gt;Kane&lt;/a&gt; which I picked up in
paperback in the mid 1980s, but he was equally talented as a writer
and editor of horror.  I &lt;em&gt;have&lt;/em&gt; read his British Fantasy Award-winning
story &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122112/http://www.thecimmerian.com/the-terror-of-the-absurd-karl-edward-wagners-sticks/"&gt;Sticks&lt;/a&gt; and it had a considerable effect on me, but I don't
remember every reading any of his other horror stories.  The &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/"&gt;ISFDB&lt;/a&gt;
has what seems a very complete &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?153"&gt;page&lt;/a&gt; listing his writings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I aim to fix that.  I've now got copies of the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centipede_Press"&gt;Centipede Press&lt;/a&gt;
collections &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pl.cgi?372768"&gt;Where the Summer Ends&lt;/a&gt; (2012) and &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pl.cgi?372769"&gt;Walk on the Wild
Side&lt;/a&gt; (2012) and I'll be reading them soon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;dl class="footnote brackets"&gt;
&lt;dt class="label" id="hf"&gt;&lt;span class="brackets"&gt;&lt;a class="fn-backref" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/#id1"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd&gt;&lt;p&gt;A term he vastly preferred to “Sword &amp;amp; Sorcery”.  Or maybe he
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://thesilverkey.blogspot.com/2019/10/remembering-karl-edward-wagner-1945-1994.html"&gt;preferred&lt;/a&gt; (note 1 at the bottom of the post) “epic fantasy” or
“dark fantasy”.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;/dl&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>dark fantasy</category><category>epic fantasy</category><category>fiction</category><category>heroic fantasy</category><category>horror</category><category>kane</category><category>karl edward wagner</category><category>sword &amp; sorcery</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 12 Mar 2020 19:35:02 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Recent Reading: F. Paul Wilson</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2012/03/07/f-paul-wilson/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;cite&gt;The Tomb&lt;/cite&gt;, by F. Paul Wilson.  A &lt;cite class="series"&gt;Repairman Jack&lt;/cite&gt; novel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first, I think, followed by &lt;cite&gt;Legacies&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Conspiracies&lt;/cite&gt;*, &lt;cite&gt;All
the Rage&lt;/cite&gt;*, &lt;cite&gt;Hosts&lt;/cite&gt;*, &lt;cite&gt;The Haunted Air&lt;/cite&gt;* , &lt;cite&gt;Gateways&lt;/cite&gt;*,
&lt;cite&gt;Crisscross&lt;/cite&gt;*, &lt;cite&gt;Infernal&lt;/cite&gt;*, &lt;cite&gt;Harbingers&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Bloodline&lt;/cite&gt;*, &lt;cite&gt;By the
Sword&lt;/cite&gt;*, &lt;cite&gt;Ground Zero&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Fatal Error&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;The Dark at the End&lt;/cite&gt;.
There are also three young adult novels: &lt;cite&gt;Jack: Secret Histories&lt;/cite&gt;,
&lt;cite&gt;Jack: Secret Circles&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Jack: Secret Vengeance&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;* = read.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</description><category>horror</category><category>recent reading</category><category>science fiction</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2012/03/07/f-paul-wilson/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 07 Mar 2012 05:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Recent Reading: Laurell K. Hamilton</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2009/12/09/laurell-k.-hamilton/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;ul&gt;
